# Rk Caching

The simplification I'd actually reach for: demand-driven LMax with monotonic growth
Don't coordinate LMax at registration at all. Instead:

The requester (Direct/Exchange) already knows its shell l's, so it passes the required LMax into the lookup.
The cached Rk stores Rabcd_k up to whatever LMax it's been asked for so far; if a later request needs more k terms, it computes the extra terms and appends — it never shrinks, never gets evicted, never gets rebuilt.
That collapses the whole apparatus:

Register() becomes trivial — just grouper index assignment. No maxl, no eviction, no rebuild.
isSupported disappears (the value object stops knowing about cache clients).
The nasty cross-basis case ("light atom builds R^k at LMax=1, heavy atom later needs it at LMax=3 and gets a too-small entry") becomes a top-up, not a correctness landmine.
The complexity moves from global registration coordination to local lazy growth inside the value object — which is far easier to get right and to reason about. It's a real refactor (Gaussian/Slater derivative tables and the BSpline moment tables all need to grow incrementally rather than build-to-LMax), so it's a "next time you're in here" move, not an emergency.

# High precision integration tests.
You're definitely not the first — this is the classic golden-master / characterization test tension, and the standard resolution is a two-axis split. The key move is to stop treating "protect the hard-won numbers" and "catch code regressions" as the same test, because they have very different cost/frequency profiles.

# Data flow diagrams
The name to ask for: a data-flow diagram (DFD) — processes (functions) transforming data, with the data artifacts named on the edges and streams that fork/merge. (Colloquially "pipeline diagram"; the precise term is data-flow diagram. Just say "draw me a dataflow diagram of X" and I'll produce this style.)

